### Q18. What is event handling in React?

**Answer:**
React handles events using **camelCase** syntax and passes a **function reference** (not a string). React uses **Synthetic Events** — a cross-browser wrapper around native events.

```jsx
// ✅ React way (camelCase + function reference)
<button onClick={handleClick}>Click</button>

// ❌ HTML way (lowercase + string)
<button onclick="handleClick()">Click</button>
```

**Examples:**

```jsx
function Form() {
  // Basic event handler
  const handleClick = () => {
    console.log('Button clicked');
  };

  // Event with event object
  const handleChange = (e) => {
    console.log(e.target.value);
  };

  // Prevent default behavior
  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    console.log('Form submitted');
  };

  // Pass arguments
  const handleDelete = (id) => {
    console.log('Delete item:', id);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input onChange={handleChange} />
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Submit</button>
      {/* ✅ Passing arguments — wrap in arrow function */}
      <button onClick={() => handleDelete(42)}>Delete</button>
      {/* ❌ Wrong — this calls immediately on render */}
      {/* <button onClick={handleDelete(42)}>Delete</button> */}
    </form>
  );
}
```

