### Q27. What is the difference between Controlled and Uncontrolled Components?

**Answer:**

**Controlled Component:** React state is the **single source of truth** for the form input.

```jsx
function ControlledInput() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');

  return (
    <input
      value={value}                            // React controls the value
      onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)} // Every keystroke updates state
    />
  );
}
```

**Uncontrolled Component:** The **DOM itself** stores the form data. You access it via `ref`.

```jsx
function UncontrolledInput() {
  const inputRef = useRef();

  const handleSubmit = () => {
    console.log(inputRef.current.value); // Read from DOM
  };

  return <input ref={inputRef} defaultValue="initial" />;
}
```

| Feature            | Controlled               | Uncontrolled             |
| ------------------ | ------------------------ | ------------------------ |
| Data source        | React state              | DOM                      |
| Validation         | ✅ Real-time, easy       | ⚠️ On submit only        |
| Dynamic UI updates | ✅ Easy                  | ❌ Hard                  |
| Performance        | ⚠️ Re-renders on typing  | ✅ Fewer re-renders      |
| When to use        | Most forms               | File inputs, simple forms |

**Interview answer:** *"I prefer controlled components because they give me full control over the form data, making validation, conditional rendering, and data formatting easy. I use uncontrolled components only for file inputs or when integrating with non-React libraries."*

