### Q28. What is `React.memo()`?

**Answer:**
`React.memo` is a **Higher Order Component (HOC)** that **memoizes a functional component**. It prevents re-rendering if the **props haven't changed** (shallow comparison).

```jsx
const ExpensiveList = React.memo(function ExpensiveList({ items }) {
  console.log('Rendering ExpensiveList'); // only when `items` changes
  return (
    <ul>
      {items.map(item => <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>)}
    </ul>
  );
});

// Custom comparison function
const MemoizedUser = React.memo(UserCard, (prevProps, nextProps) => {
  return prevProps.userId === nextProps.userId; // only re-render if userId changes
});
```

**When to use:**
- Component renders the **same output** for the same props
- Component re-renders **frequently** with **unchanged props**
- Component has **expensive rendering logic**

**When NOT to use:**
- Component's props change on almost every render
- Component is cheap to render
- Don't wrap everything — measure first!

