### Q43. What are Concurrent Features in React 18?

**Answer:**
Concurrent rendering lets React **prepare multiple versions of the UI at the same time** and prioritize urgent updates over less important ones.

**Key features:**

**1. Automatic Batching:**
```jsx
// React 18 batches ALL state updates (even in setTimeout, promises)
setTimeout(() => {
  setCount(1);
  setFlag(true);
  // React 18: ONE re-render ✅ (auto-batched)
  // React 17: TWO re-renders ❌
}, 1000);
```

**2. `useTransition` — mark updates as non-urgent:**
```jsx
function SearchPage() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);
  const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();

  const handleChange = (e) => {
    setQuery(e.target.value);              // Urgent — update input immediately

    startTransition(() => {
      setResults(filterData(e.target.value)); // Non-urgent — can be interrupted
    });
  };

  return (
    <>
      <input value={query} onChange={handleChange} />
      {isPending ? <p>Filtering...</p> : <ResultsList results={results} />}
    </>
  );
}
```

**3. `useDeferredValue` — defer a value:**
```jsx
function SearchResults({ query }) {
  const deferredQuery = useDeferredValue(query);
  // deferredQuery lags behind `query` — React renders with old value first
  // then updates when resources are available
  const results = useMemo(() => filterItems(deferredQuery), [deferredQuery]);
  return <List items={results} />;
}
```

